50|$|But {{if there}} <b>is</b> clear intent <b>to</b> <b>be</b> contractually bound, the {{presumption}} is rebutted. In Merritt v Merritt 1970, a separation agreement between estranged spouses <b>was</b> <b>enforceable.</b> In Beswick v Beswick 1967 an uncle's agreement {{to sell a}} coal delivery business <b>to</b> his nephew <b>was</b> <b>enforceable.</b> In Errington v Errington 1952, a father's promise to his son and daughter-in-law that they could live in (and ultimately own) a house if they paid off {{the balance of the}} mortgage, <b>was</b> an <b>enforceable</b> unilateral contract.|$|R
